. There may well have been some confusion with   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Lawton was born in 1466, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Cinlislmi Lawton. He died in 1481, in his hometown, at the age of 15."},"et":{"1466–1481":"1466–1481","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1481–1511":"1481–1511","1511":"1511","1466":"1466","1481":"1481","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1466–1481":"1466–1481","1466–Female":"1466–Kuollut","1481–1511":"1481–1511","1511":"1511","1466":"1466","1481":"1481","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, Englanti, 